"A digital necropolis is a conceptual space dedicated to the archiving and simulation of obsolete technologies. The goal is to reconstruct the architectural, software, and experiential aspects of these vanished machines, creating a virtual ‘museum’ of forgotten computing power. The project will begin with the selection of three technologies: a 1980s Macintosh SE, a 1970s IBM System/360 mainframe, and an early 1990s Sega Genesis gaming console. Each technology will be represented in detail, including its physical design, its operating system, its software applications, and the types of experiences it offered. This process will involve extensive research, archival documentation, software emulation, 3D modeling, and sensory simulations to evoke the feeling of using these machines. The project is intended to explore the relationship between technology, memory, and cultural change, and to generate new insights into the evolution of computing. Further research will be conducted into the philosophical implications of digital preservation and the possibility of creating ‘ghosts’ of past technologies."